#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:11
msgid "A quadratic Hamiltonian is a Hamiltonian of the form"
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:13
msgid ""
"H =\n"
"\\sum_{j, k} M_{jk} a^\\dagger_j a_k\n"
"+ \\frac12 \\sum_{j, k}\n"
"    (\\Delta_{jk} a^\\dagger_j a^\\dagger_k + \\Delta^*_{jk} a_k a_j)\n"
"+ \\text{constant}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:22
msgid ""
"where :math:`M` is a Hermitian matrix (:math:`M^\\dagger = M`) and "
":math:`\\Delta` is an antisymmetric matrix (:math:`\\Delta^T = "
"-\\Delta`), and the :math:`\\{a_j^\\dagger\\}` are fermionic creation "
"operators which satisfy the anticommutation relations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:24
msgid ""
"\\begin{align}\n"
"    a_j a_k + a_k a_j &= 0 \\\\\n"
"    a_j a^\\dagger_k + a^\\dagger_k a_j &= \\delta_{pq}\n"
"\\end{align}."
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:32
msgid ""
"Quadratic Hamiltonians are an important class of Hamiltonians that are "
"classically tractable. Their eigenstates are called fermionic Gaussian "
"states, and they can be efficiently prepared on a quantum computer. "
"Qiskit Nature includes the ``QuadraticHamiltonian`` class for "
"representing quadratic Hamiltonians."
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:34
msgid ""
"Of course, the ``FermionicOp`` class can also be used to represent any "
"quadratic Hamiltonian. The reason to have a class specifically for "
"quadratic Hamiltonians is that they support special numerical routines "
"that involve performing linear algebra on the matrices :math:`M` and "
":math:`\\Delta`. The internal representation format of ``FermionicOp`` is"
" not suitable for these routines."
msgstr ""

