#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:388
msgid ""
"When the antisymmetric part :math:`\\Delta = 0`, then the Hamiltonian "
"conserves the number of particles. In this case, the basis change only "
"needs to mix creation operators, not annihilation operators:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:390
msgid ""
"\\begin{pmatrix}\n"
"b^\\dagger_1 \\\\\n"
"\\vdots \\\\\n"
"b^\\dagger_N \\\\\n"
"\\end{pmatrix}\n"
"= W\n"
"\\begin{pmatrix}\n"
"a^\\dagger_1 \\\\\n"
"\\vdots \\\\\n"
"a^\\dagger_N \\\\\n"
"\\end{pmatrix},"
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:405
msgid ""
"where now :math:`W` is an :math:`N \\times N` matrix. Furthermore, the "
"orbital energies :math:`\\{\\varepsilon_j\\}` are allowed to be negative."
msgstr ""

#: ../../tutorials/11_quadratic_hamiltonian_and_slater_determinants.ipynb:515
msgid ""
"In this special case, the eigenstates are called Slater determinants, and"
" a more efficient algorithm is used to prepare them. This algorithm is "
"accessed by using the ``SlaterDeterminant`` class instead of "
"``FermionicGaussianState``. ``SlaterDeterminant`` does not take the "
"occupied orbitals as input. Instead, the shape of the transformation "
"matrix is allowed to vary. It should be an :math:`\\eta \\times N` matrix"
" where :math:`\\eta` is the number of particles."
msgstr ""

